body: That is something we should work on. Creating a Resnet 50/101 Versions/Portals.
@tamasbalassa yes you can train with that cfg here. See https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov3/issues/698
@glenn-jocher  I think he was talking about a pure ResNet50 model. The classic one.

@FranciscoReveriano we can train resnet50.cfg as well, and most other cfgs available. A good source of darknet cfgs is here:
https://github.com/AlexeyAB/darknet/tree/master/cfg

Thanks for the replies, Im glad about the discussion above.

Just to clarify, I already used the mentioned _csresnext50-panet-spp_ and with it I got the far best results.

My point would be exactly the same as @FranciscoReveriano's. I checked AlexeyAB's repo with the cfg's, but I was not sure how could I apply(/combine) them directly.
That is extremely interesting. I think the Repo would be aided if we made a README showing how to use a ResNet50 Backbone with Yolo. Similar to  Alexey repo.

Yes, and it's interest that @tamasbalassa got good results with csresnext50-panet-spp, as I've always gotten worse results on COCO using it. See https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov3/issues/698#issuecomment-564358996

@glenn-jocher Yes, I trained with the recent copy of the repo. Actually I compared these two (resnext vs. yolospp) for the first time, and the results look interesting. 
Training time:
- yolospp ~1.6hrs
- resnext ~1.3hrs 

![results](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3785204/75457779-2bde6280-597d-11ea-8346-ad1794860abb.png)

I will test this model today. So we can compare results. 
How would you combine Resnet101 with Yolov3 in this repo? I don't mind setting the rest of the backbones up and making a pull request.
